[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] In computer science, **automatic programming** is a type of computer programming in which some mechanism generates a computer program, to allow human programmers to write the code at a higher abstraction level.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] There has been little agreement on the precise definition of automatic programming, mostly because its meaning has changed over time.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] David Parnas, tracing the history of "automatic programming" in published research, noted that in the 1940s it described automation of the manual process of punching paper tape.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Later it referred to translation of high-level programming languages like Fortran and ALGOL.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] One of the earliest programs identifiable as a compiler is named Autocode.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Program synthesis is one type of automatic programming where a procedure is created from scratch, based on mathematical requirements.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Mildred Koss, an early UNIVAC programmer, explains: "Writing machine code involved several tedious steps—breaking down a process into discrete instructions, assigning specific memory locations to all the commands, and managing the I/O buffers.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] After following these steps to implement mathematical routines, a sub-routine library, and sorting programs, our task was to look at the larger programming process.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] We needed to understand how we might reuse tested code and have the machine help in programming.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] As we programmed, we examined the process and tried to think of ways to abstract these steps to incorporate them into higher-level language.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] The goal is to improve programmer productivity.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] It is often related to code-reuse topics such as component-based software engineering.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Modern programming languages are well supported by tools like Json4Swift (Swift) and Json2Kotlin (Kotlin).
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] These application generators supported COBOL inserts and overrides.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] A macro processor, such as the C preprocessor, which replaces patterns in source code according to relatively simple rules, is a simple form of source-code generator.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Source-to-source code generation tools also exist.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Large language models such as ChatGPT are capable of generating a program's source code from a description of the program given in a natural language.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Many relational database management systems (RDBMS) provide a function that will export the content of the database as SQL data definition queries, which may then be executed to re-import the tables and their data, or migrate them to another RDBMS.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Some languages use *annotations* to generate source code and inject it.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] For example, this is done in Java and Kotlin using annotations, for example the Project Lombok library which runs at compile time with an annotation processor.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] There has been a C++ proposal to add token sequence injection using compile-time reflective programming (reflection).
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] A low-code development platform (LCDP) is software that provides an environment programmers use to create application software through graphical user interfaces and configuration instead of traditional computer programming.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Vibe coding is a software development practice assisted by artificial intelligence (AI) where the software developer describes a project or task in a prompt to a large language model (LLM) which generates source code automatically.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Vibe coding may involve accepting AI-generated code without thorough review of the output, instead relying on results and follow-up prompts to guide changes.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] The term was coined in February 2025 by computer scientist Andrej Karpathy, a co-founder of OpenAI and former AI leader at Tesla.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Merriam-Webster listed the term in March 2025 as a "slang & trending" expression.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] It was named the *Collins English Dictionary* Word of the Year for 2025.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Advocates of vibe coding say that it allows even amateur programmers to produce software without the extensive training and skills required for software engineering.
[src:openapi-codegen/automatic-programming] Critics point out a lack of accountability, maintainability, and an increased risk of introducing security vulnerabilities in the resulting software.
