[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] The **OpenAPI Specification** (**OAS**), previously known as the **Swagger Specification**, is a specification for a machine-readable interface definition language for describing, producing, consuming and visualizing web services.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Originally developed to support the Swagger framework, it became a separate project in 2015, overseen by the OpenAPI Initiative, an open-source collaboration project of the Linux Foundation.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] An OpenAPI Description (OAD) represents a formal description of an API that tools can use to generate code, documentation, test cases, and more.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Swagger development began in early 2010 by Tony Tam, who was working at online dictionary company Wordnik.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] In March 2015, SmartBear Software acquired the open-source Swagger API specification from Reverb Technologies, Wordnik's parent company.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] In November 2015, SmartBear announced that it was donating the Swagger specification to a new organization called the OpenAPI Initiative, under the sponsorship of the Linux Foundation.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Other founding member companies included 3scale, Apigee, Capital One, Google, IBM, Intuit, Microsoft, PayPal, and Restlet.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] On 1 January 2016, the Swagger specification was renamed the OpenAPI Specification (OAS) and was moved to a new GitHub repository.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Two somewhat similar technologies, MuleSoft's RESTful API Modeling Language (RAML) and Apiary's API Blueprint, had been developed around the same time as what was then still called the Swagger Specification.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] The producers of both formats later joined the OpenAPI Initiative: Apiary in 2016 and MuleSoft in 2017.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] In July 2017, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.0.0 of its specification.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] In February 2021, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.1.0.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] In September 2025, the OpenAPI Initiative released version 3.2.0 of the OAS.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Notable features include structured tags, first-class streaming media type support, support for arbitrary HTTP methods, clearer example semantics for serializations, OAuth2 device flow and metadata enhancements, and clarified path templating and routing semantics.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] The OAS describes the format for OpenAPI Descriptions (OADs), which can be used by a variety of applications, libraries, and tools.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Applications can use OADs to automatically generate documentation of methods, parameters and data models.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] This helps keep the documentation, client libraries and source code in sync.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] When an OAD is used to generate source code stubs for servers, the process is called scaffolding.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] The paradigm of agreeing on an API contract first and then programming business logic afterwards, in contrast to coding the program first and then writing a retrospective description of its behavior as the contract, is called contract-first development.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Since the interface is determined before any code is written, downstream developers can mock the server behavior and start testing right away.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] In this sense, contract-first development is also a practice of shift-left testing.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Specification is language-agnostic.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] With OpenAPI's declarative resource specification, clients can understand and consume services without knowledge of server implementation or access to the server code.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] The OpenAPI Initiative sponsored APIStrat from 2017 to 2019, converting it into the API Specifications Confererence (ASC) from 2020 to 2022.
[src:openapi-codegen/openapi-specification] Starting in 2023, the initiative has instead sponsored OpenAPI tracks at multiple conferences throughout the year.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] The Swagger API project was created in 2011 by Tony Tam, technical co-founder of the dictionary site Wordnik.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] During the development of Wordnik's products, the need for automation of API documentation and client SDK generation became a major source of frustration.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Tam designed a simple JSON representation of the API, building upon the flexibility of the HTTP protocol and using many features of tooling built for the SOAP protocol.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] The concept for the user interface was proposed by Ayush Gupta, who suggested that an interactive user interface would benefit end users who wished to "try out" and develop against the API.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Ramesh Pidikiti led implementation of the initial code generator and designer/developer Zeke Sikelianos coined the name Swagger.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] The Swagger API project was made open source in September 2011.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Soon after release, a number of new components were added to the project, including a stand-alone validator and support for Node.js and Ruby on Rails.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] In Swagger's early years, modest traction came from small companies and independent developers.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] HTTP APIs typically did not have a machine-readable description mechanism, and Swagger provided a simple and discoverable way to do so.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Tony was invited to a meeting with some of the API industry's thought leaders including John Musser (ProgrammableWeb), Marsh Gardiner (Apigee, now a Google product), Marco Palladino (Kong), and Kin Lane (API Evangelist) to discuss a standardization effort around API descriptions.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] While the meeting did not yield a concrete plan to do so, it put Swagger on the map as a critical innovation in the API space.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Helped by the use of the Apache 2.0 open-source license, a number of products and online services began including Swagger in their offerings, which accelerated quickly after adoption by Apigee, Intuit, Microsoft, IBM and others who began to publicly endorse the Swagger project.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Shortly after Swagger was created, alternative structures for describing HTTP APIs were introduced, the most popular being API Blueprint in April 2013 and RESTful API Modeling Language (RAML) in September 2013.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] While these competing products had stronger financial backing than Swagger, they initially focused on different use cases from Swagger, and as of mid-2014, Swagger interest was growing more quickly than the combination of the two others [source: Google Trends].
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] In November 2015, SmartBear Software, the company that maintained Swagger, announced that it was helping create a new organization, under the sponsorship of the Linux Foundation, called the OpenAPI Initiative.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] A variety of companies, including Google, IBM, and Microsoft are founding members.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] On 1 January 2016, the Swagger specification was renamed to OpenAPI Specification, and was moved to a new software repository on GitHub.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] While the specification itself was not changed, this renaming signified the split between the API description format and the open-source tooling.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] As of July 2017, Swagger tools were downloaded over 100,000 times per day, according to hosting repositories Sonatype and npm.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Swagger's open-source tooling usage can be broken up into different use cases: development, interaction with APIs, and documentation.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] When creating APIs, Swagger tooling may be used to automatically generate an Open API document based on the code itself.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] This embeds the API description in the source code of a project and is informally called code-first or bottom-up API development.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Alternatively, using Swagger Codegen, developers can decouple the source code from the Open API document, and generate client and server code directly from the design.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] This makes it possible to defer the coding aspect.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Using the Swagger Codegen project, end users generate client SDKs directly from the OpenAPI document, reducing the need for human-generated client code.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] As of August 2017, the Swagger Codegen project supported over 50 different languages and formats for client SDK generation.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] When described by an OpenAPI document, Swagger open-source tooling may be used to interact directly with the API through the Swagger UI.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] This project allows connections directly to live APIs through an interactive, HTML-based user interface.
[src:openapi-codegen/swagger-software] Requests can be made directly from the UI and the options explored by the user of the interface.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:openapi-codegen/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
